Culture.name: Coruscanti
Culture.text: The trillions of sentient beings who inhabit the ecumenopolis world of Coruscant are known as the Coruscanti. The Coruscanti are not just one species, but are comprised of a multitude of species from all across the galaxy. The people of Coruscant lead very diverse lives, some barely scrape a living in the city-planet's underworld, while others lead extremely lavish lives dwelling in places such as 500 Republica. Generally, the Coruscanti are a very principled and well educated people, and are far better off than those living in many of the outer rim worlds.

Culture.name: 212th Attack Battalion

Culture.name: 104th Attack Battalion
Culture.text: Known mostly for their prowess with heavy weapons and their veracious marksmen, the 104th Attack Battalion is one of the deadliest outfits in the Grand Army of the Republic. The 104th have taken on the moniker Wolfpack, paying homage to Clone Commander Wolffe, who serves under Jedi General Plo Koon. During the Battle of Abregado, the Wolfpack lost much of its forces, losing the maroon markings they had at the start of the war. To honor their fallen comrades, they are now marked by a flint grey pattern, with the distinctive Wolfpack sigil proudly displayed upon their armor.

Culture.name: Separatist
Culture.text: Colloquially referred to as Separatists, these people are of worlds that currently oppose the Galactic Republic. From Mustafar to Bastion, the Separatists hail from every corner of the galaxy, united by one common ideal, freedom from the bureaucracy and corruption of the Republic. Planets within the Separatist dominion range from agriworlds to titanic manufacturing worlds. Their combined might and dedication to the cause makes them a formidable opponent to the Republic and its inhabitants.

Culture.name: New Mandalorian
Culture.text: Disavowing the warrior culture of the Mandalorians, the New Mandalorians choose diplomacy over blasters and Beskar'gam. This new way of thinking has been spearheaded by Duchess Satine Kryze who seeks to replace the lust for battle that Mandalorians are notorious for and instead opt for a more diplomatic approach with other governments. This new ideology has spread to much of the culture, leading to new pursuits such as the arts and higher education, creating a society of scholars rather than soldiers.

Culture.name: Death Watch
Culture.text: Stalwart defenders of the true Mandalorian culture, the Death Watch passionately oppose the pacifist ways of the New Mandalorians. Branded terrorists and fanatical zealots by many in the galaxy, these people view themselves as true Mando'ade, donning their Beskar'gam openly and proudly. They still hold true to Mandalorian traditions, such as following the Resol'nare, engaging in rigorous training exercises, and hoping to face their enemies in combat.

Culture.name: Galactic Criminal
Culture.text: The scum and villains of the galaxy, criminals engage in any act that brings in credits regardless of the morality of their ventures. Selling spice on the black market, trading in slaves, ransacking cargo freighters, it's all the same to them so long as they bring in currency. The upstart criminals tend to join the ranks of one of the Five Crime Syndicates, hoping to survive long enough to lead a crew and start their own venture. Their line of work has placed them in the crosshairs of every civilized government, it's a risky profession but a well paying one.

Culture.name: Naboo
Culture.text: The Naboolians are a mostly peaceful people, favoring art and beauty over blasters and blades. Around 3900 BBY, the first humans crash landed on Naboo, fleeing a civil war on their homeworld of Grizmallt. They then established small farming colonies and expanded to nearby systems. During this time, they engaged in many gruesome battles with the native Gungans. These skirmishes between the two peoples only ceased when the Gungans and Naboolians began fighting themselves. This infighting ceased when a general by the name of Jafan united the Naboolians, bringing peace. Around 840 years ago, the Naboo joined the Republic, ushering in a new era of prosperity.

Culture.name: Geonosian
Culture.text: The Geonosians are an insectoid species of the planet Geonosis. They adhere to a strict caste system where each hive is lead by a queen who lays eggs that spawn the next generation of Geonosians. Below the queen and the other ranking members, lie the warrior caste who boast both wings and a thick exoskeleton. At the lowest levels of society lie the drones, who simply live to work in the great factories that are greatly prized and revered by the Geonosians. They believe hard work and dedication to be the most noble of causes.

Culture.name: Zygerrian
Culture.text: The Zygerrians were a once great empire during the time of the Old Republic, supplying slave labor to all parts of the galaxy. With the vast wealth generated by selling slaves, they lived lavish lives on their homeworld of Zygeria, erecting massive palaces and villas, as well as slave markets where the galaxy's wealthy could purchase laboreres. Today however, much of the influence and wealth they had prior has vastly diminished. They now have allied themselves with Count Dooku and the Separatists, hoping to rebuild their once great Zygerrian Slave Empire.
